1. Instant / Manual Trigger Flows

No trigger means no timer.
You could leave it untouched for years, and it will still run the moment you manually trigger it.
No expiration. No timeout. It just waits.

2. Automated Flows (e.g., SharePoint "When an item is created")

Same idea.
They don’t “expire.”
If the trigger event happens, the flow wakes up and runs.
You can come back in 2 years, create a SharePoint item, and boom, it runs.

3. Scheduled Flows

If it’s on a timer (e.g., every day at 9 AM) and the schedule is valid, it’ll fire forever unless:

you turn off the flow

you delete the flow

your license expires or environment is suspended

Otherwise, it will just keep running.

4. Flows Waiting on “Delay” or “Delay Until”

This is where the rules get strict:

Microsoft enforces a 30-day maximum run time for a single flow instance.

So if your flow is:

Waiting on approval

Stuck on a Delay Until

Paused because of a condition

Then after 30 days of inactivity, it fails automatically with a timeout error:
"Flow run timed out because it has been running for more than 30 days."

5. Flows Using Approvals

Approvals follow the same 30-day expiration unless you’re using Power Automate Approvals with Power Apps Premium / managed Environments where some newer features extend to 60+ days, but the standard rule is:

A flow approval cannot wait more than 30 days.

Summary (quick version)

Untriggered flows can sit idle forever.

Flow run instances can only stay alive 30 days max before timing out.

Manual/automated triggers don’t expire.

Delay / Approval / Waits expire after 30 days.



