1. “Flow will not be turned off due to lack of activity” (Premium license)

This refers ONLY to the flow itself, not the flow run.

Microsoft used to auto-disable flows that hadn’t been triggered in 90 days in the Standard tier.

If you have:

a Premium license

or the flow lives in a Premium / enterprise environment

then Microsoft will NOT automatically turn off your flow, even if nobody triggers it for 2 years.

So the flow stays ON forever.
This is about the flow configuration, not the flow execution.

✅ Meaning:
Your flow won’t be deactivated from inactivity.

❌ Does NOT affect:
How long a single flow instance can run.



2. The 30-day timeout rule

This is a hard platform limit, even with Premium licensing.

A running flow instance cannot stay alive more than 30 days, no matter what license you have.

This applies to:

Delay

Delay Until

Approvals

Do Until loops waiting

Anything that causes the flow to pause or stay in a “waiting” state

Once a flow run hits 30 days, it dies with:
"The flow run timed out because it ran for more than 30 days."

This rule applies:
✅ In Standard environments
✅ In Premium environments
✅ Even with Process / Per-user / Per-flow licenses

No license bypasses this.


So putting it together:
Premium license

Your flow won’t auto-disable due to not being triggered ✔️

You can leave it idle for years ✔️

Flow run waiting 30+ days

Still times out ❌

Premium license doesn’t remove timeout ❌



Quick example to make it clear
Scenario A:

A flow has a trigger “When an item is created.”
No one adds an item for 18 months.

✅ Flow stays active with Premium
✅ It will still run the moment someone adds an item
(No limitation here.)



Scenario B:

A flow runs today and hits a Delay Until 90 days later.

⛔ The flow run will fail at day 30
✅ The flow itself stays enabled, though
❌ Licensing doesn’t extend run-time limits
